name: Module
comment:
Module contributes configuration information to an Injector by providing a collection of type bindings that specify how each type is created.

When an injector is created, it copies its configuration information from a module. Defining additional type bindings after an injector is created has no effect on that injector.

reflector.name: reflector
reflector.comment: A angular/di.TypeReflector for the module to look up constructors for types when toFactory and toValue are not specified. This is done with mirroring or pre-generated typeFactories.

withReflector.name: withReflector
withReflector.comment: Use a custom reflector instead of the default. Useful for testing purposes.

bind.name: bind
bind.comment:
Registers a binding for a given angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.type.

The default behavior is to simply instantiate the type.

The following parameters can be specified:

  • angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.toImplementation: The given type will be instantiated using the new operator and the resulting instance will be injected.

  • angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.toFactory: The result of the factory function called with the types of angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.inject as arguments is the value that will be injected.

  • angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.toValue: The given value will be injected.

  • angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.toInstanceOf: An instance of the given type will be fetched with DI. This is shorthand for toFactory: (x) => x, inject: X.

  • angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.withAnnotation: Type decorated with additional annotation.

Up to one (0 or 1) of the following parameters can be specified at the same time: angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.toImplementation, angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.toFactory, angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.toValue, angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind.toInstanceOf.

bindByKey.name: bindByKey
bindByKey.comment: Same as angular/angular-formatter.Module.bind except it takes angular/di-key.Key instead of [Type] [withAnnotation] combination. Faster.

install.name: install
install.comment: Copies all bindings of angular/angular-formatter.Module.install.module into this one. Overwriting when conflicts are found.

hashCode.name: hashCode
hashCode.comment:
Get a hash code for this object.

All objects have hash codes. Hash codes are guaranteed to be the same for objects that are equal when compared using the equality operator ==. Other than that there are no guarantees about the hash codes. They will not be consistent between runs and there are no distribution guarantees.

If a subclass overrides angular/angular-formatter.Module.hashCode it should override the equality operator as well to maintain consistency.

runtimeType.name: runtimeType
runtimeType.comment: A representation of the runtime type of the object.

==.comment:
The equality operator.

The default behavior for all dart-core.Objects is to return true if and only if this and angular/angular-formatter.Module.==.other are the same object.

Override this method to specify a different equality relation on a class. The overriding method must still be an equivalence relation. That is, it must be:

  • Total: It must return a boolean for all arguments. It should never throw or return null.

  • Reflexive: For all objects o, o == o must be true.

  • Symmetric: For all objects o1 and o2, o1 == o2 and o2 == o1 must either both be true, or both be false.

  • Transitive: For all objects o1, o2, and o3, if o1 == o2 and o2 == o3 are true, then o1 == o3 must be true.

The method should also be consistent over time, so equality of two objects should not change over time, or at least only change if one of the objects was modified.

If a subclass overrides the equality operator it should override the angular/angular-formatter.Module.hashCode method as well to maintain consistency.

noSuchMethod.name: noSuchMethod
noSuchMethod.comment:
angular/angular-formatter.Module.noSuchMethod is invoked when users invoke a non-existent method on an object. The name of the method and the arguments of the invocation are passed to angular/angular-formatter.Module.noSuchMethod in an dart-core.Invocation. If angular/angular-formatter.Module.noSuchMethod returns a value, that value becomes the result of the original invocation.

The default behavior of angular/angular-formatter.Module.noSuchMethod is to throw a dart-core.NoSuchMethodError.

toString.name: toString
toString.comment: Returns a string representation of this object.
